SIMPLE: wring
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wring
<hw>Wring</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wrung</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>Obs.</mark>
<conjf>Wringed</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wringing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wringen</ets>, AS.
<ets>wringan</ets>; akin to LG. & D. <ets>wringen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>ringan</ets> to struggle, G. <ets>ringen</ets>, Sw.
<ets>vr⟦aum⟧nga</ets> to distort, Dan. <ets>vringle</ets> to twist. Cf.
<er>Wrangle</er>, <er>Wrench</er>, <er>Wrong</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To twist and compress; to turn and strain with
violence; to writhe; to squeeze hard; to pinch; <as>as, to
<ex>wring</ex> clothes in washing</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Earnestly
<xex>wringing</xex> Waverley's hand.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir W. Scott.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wring</xex> him by the nose.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[His steed] so sweat that men might him <qex>wring</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king began to find where his shoe did <qex>wring</qex>
him.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The priest shall bring it [a dove] unto the altar, and
<qex>wring</qex> off his head.</q> <rj><qau>Lev. i. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to pain; to distress; to torment; to
torture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too much grieved and <qex>wrung</qex> by an uneasy and strait
fortune.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Didst thou taste but half the griefs⟦br⟧
That <qex>wring</qex> my soul, thou couldst not talk thus coldly.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To distort; to pervert; to wrest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How dare men thus <qex>wring</qex> the Scriptures?</q>
<rj><qau>Whitgift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To extract or obtain by twisting and compressing; to
squeeze or press (out); hence, to extort; to draw forth by violence, or
against resistance or repugnance; -- usually with <xex>out</xex> or
<xex>form</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your overkindness doth <qex>wring</qex> tears from me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He rose up early on the morrow, and thrust the fleece together,
and <qex>wringed</qex> the dew out of the fleece.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. vi.
38.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To subject to extortion; to afflict, or oppress, in
order to enforce compliance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>wring</qex> the widow from her 'customed right.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The merchant adventures have been often wronged and
<qex>wringed</qex> to the quick.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To bend or strain out of its
position; <as>as, to <ex>wring</ex> a mast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wring
<hw>Wring</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To writhe; to twist, as with
anguish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is all men's office to speak patience⟦br⟧
To those that <qex>wring</qex> under the load of sorrow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Look where the sister of the king of France⟦br⟧
Sits <qex>wringing</qex> of her hands, and beats her breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Marlowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wring
<hw>Wring</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A writhing, as in anguish; a
twisting; a griping.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wringbolt</ent>⟦br⟧
